  "prompt": "I'm going through a midlife crisis at 18. What should I do?",
  "response": "Feeling like you're having a midlife crisis at 18 can be overwhelming, but it's important to understand that you're experiencing a period of significant change and self-reflection, which is common at this age. Here are some steps you can take:\n\n1. **Accept and Acknowledge Your Feelings**: It's okay to feel confused or anxious. Acknowledge your emotions instead of suppressing them. Journaling or talking to a trusted friend can help you process your feelings.\n\n2. **Set Realistic Expectations**: Understand that you don't need to have everything figured out at 18. Life is a journey with many twists and turns. Allow yourself time to explore and grow.\n\n3. **Seek Guidance**: Consider talking to a counselor or therapist. They can provide professional support and help you navigate your feelings and thoughts.\n\n4. **Reflect and Identify**: Take time to reflect on what specific aspects of your life are causing distress. Identifying the root cause can help you address it more effectively.\n\n5. **Goals and Aspirations**: Think about your interests, passions, and what you enjoy doing. Start setting small, achievable goals related to these areas, which can help bring a sense of purpose and direction.\n\n6. **Connect with Others**: Seek out communities or groups that share your interests. Building new relationships and connections can provide support and new perspectives.\n\n7. **Stay Positive and Present**: Practice mindfulness and focus on being present in the moment. Activities like meditation, yoga, or exercise can help maintain a balanced perspective.\n\n8. **Educational and Career Counseling**: If career uncertainty is a significant part of your stress, seeking guidance from educational or career counseling services can provide clarity and direction.\n\n9. **Healthy Lifestyle**: Maintain a healthy lifestyle by eating well, getting regular exercise, and adequate sleep. Your physical health significantly affects your mental well-being.\n\nRemember, you're not alone in feeling this way, and many people experience similar periods of self-doubt and reevaluation. It's part of growing up and finding your path in life.",
